    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Southampton Thursday Eve Octr 8th 1835</p>
      <p>My Dearest. The Birdie was very happy, poor little thing, when it got its dear Masters letter. It was in bed this morning.-- Your organs of Geography must be sadly deranged, if you imagine that the road here passes through the New Forest, which is quite in another direction.</p>
      <p>I have got a very nice horse-- just the thing.</p>
      <p>He is safe &amp; strong, &amp; quiet to so extreme a degree, that I think he will quite break my associations of fear with riding. I rode for an hour &amp; a half this afternoon, &amp; I have also had a little walk. I have been a naughty Bird, for I contrived during my walk to gamble, &amp; to cheat also.--</p>
      <p>My gambling adventure is hardly worth detailing on paper. You will hear it when you come. Suffice it to say that any lurking propensity that might have existed in my mind for the</p>
      <p>chances, must have been nipped in the bud by the timely loss of four shillings today in exchange for a most vile basket not worth four pence. My cheating exploit is an affair of twopence. I was not aware that each person has to pay that sum for walking on the pier, &amp; nobody claimed it as it happened, which was strange. The Hen found out my act of knavery, for she asked me if I had paid it, when I returned.--</p>
      <p>The Hen won't let me read her letter to you. I am</p>
      <p>afraid she must have said I am a bad bird. I am much delighted with the look of "[pail? or piel?]-ou-bird" on paper. Ou little bird not [paith? or pieth?] yet.--</p>
      <p>The Hen is going to give the bird a silk cloak lined with fur. Is she not a dear Hen?--</p>
      <p>I have played a little on my Harp today, but my naughty won't let me play long, because she things it bad for the Bird. I assure you I am kept somewhat in order-- poor little thing that I am!--</p>
      <p>My dearest husband, Your most affecte Birdie, A. A. King</p>
    </div></body>
